liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The Rural City of Wangaratta is confident that the city is well prepared for near major flood levels that are expected to reach the city early Friday morning, and for water levels to remain high through until Sunday. Council staff and emergency services addressed residents in a virtual meeting this afternoon, and say there is no more expected weather events over the coming days set to increase flood risk. âWe have a very clear and well understood flood plan that has been in practice for a number of years now and over the last couple of floods, so that has been enacted,â Wangaratta Councilâs Director of Community and Infrastructure Marcus Goonan said. âYou will see us closing footpaths, and car parks, and roads, etc., proactively.â Mr Goonan said councilâs primary focus is on securing the cityâs levees. âEveryone would realise over the last couple of years we have been upgrading those levees,â he said. âThereâs no concern around levees at the moment. âEven at the top end of that moderate flood and even the bottom end of a major, thereâs no concern for our levee structures.â There will be no relief centre opening in Wangaratta. Residents who are concerned should ensure they have enacted their flood plan and have an emergency kit that contains medications, documentations, and a plan for their pets, and well as access to a radio or the VicEmergency app. Residents can access sandbags at the corner of Great Road and Handley Street in Wangaratta, or attend the nearby SES unit if they require staff assistance. Reporting by Erin Somerville
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Wangaratta braces for flood waters over the weekend

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: In the north of New South Wales rain has been patchy but welcome to those who were under the right cloud. For parts of the north-west like Narrabri, Moree and Walgett, the falls were a mixed bag. For those closer to Tamworth and the Liverpool Plains, the rain gods were a little friendlier. Tamworth cattle producer Neil Watson said he recorded 15mm, the most rain heâs seen for many months. âItâs just enough to put a smile on the face â¦ itâs amazing this morning, you can see a green shoot and a green tinge across the country,â he said. âIf we got that 10, 15 millimetres in a week or 10 days, it will turn things right around.â Reporting by Lara Webster

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Social media companies are now banned from facilitating sales of products on their platforms in Indonesia. TikTok has stopped its online retail operation to comply with the country's new mandate. Indonesia is the video platform's fastest-growing market. The Chinese-owned app said in a statement: "Our priority is to remain compliant with local laws and regulations." In September, China's ByteDance, which owns TikTok, said there were 2 million small businesses on TikTok Shop in Indonesia. Indonesia's Trade Minister Zulkifli Hasan said the ban aims to "prevent the domination of the algorithm and prevent the use of personal data in business interests" and "create a fair, healthy and beneficial electronic commerce ecosystem". The government announced the new regulation last month.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Fresh CoreLogic data shows it's getting harder to find a home to rent. The number of properties available is at a record low, with just 1.1 per cent of available properties vacant in September. The median weekly rent has gone up by 30.4 per cent in just three years, with people paying $137 more a week on average now than in July 2020. CoreLogic economist Eliza Owen says there is a shortfall of rental listings at a time when people are once again migrating to Australia in big numbers. "You've got real volatility with the private rental market and with the more vulnerable lower-income households." My colleague Emilia Terzon has written more about this, so I've linked it below. It has a really nifty interactive chart created by colleague Kate Ainsworth showing the least and most adorable suburbs to rent in Australia. It's a bit sobering.

Newcrest Mining ($24.14 per share) jumped as much as 1.3% after announcing a a fully franked special dividend of US$1.10 a share. While Northern Star Resources ($10.60 per share) and Evolution Mining ($3.24 per share) are both on track for their best trading day since late August.
